Our project uses a Conditional Generative Adversarial Network to convert witness sketches into realistic facial images. The system contains two neural networks: a generator and a discriminator. The generator uses an encoder–decoder architecture. The encoder extracts important facial features from the witness sketch and converts them into a latent representation. Conditional information can be added to guide image generation. The decoder reconstructs these features into a realistic color facial image. The discriminator is a CNN that compares generated images with real facial images and predicts whether they are real or fake. During training, adversarial loss improves realism, while pixel and SSIM-based losses preserve similarity to the corresponding real face. After training, the generator is deployed using Streamlit, allowing users to upload a sketch and generate a realistic facial representation in real time.

This project uses a Conditional GAN to learn the relationship between facial sketches and real photographs, then generates a realistic face from a new witness sketch using an encoder–decoder generator and a CNN-based discriminator.

I started learning and building projects using LangChain, LangGraph, LangSmith, and RAG.

Currently, I'm building a personal project called a GitHub Repository Assistant. The idea is to let developers interact with GitHub repositories using natural language. Users can ask questions like summarizing a repository, understanding the project structure, finding issues, or generating pull request descriptions.

The application uses a RAG pipeline. I load repository documents like README files and Markdown documentation using LangChain document loaders, split them into chunks, generate embeddings, and store them in ChromaDB. When a user asks a question, the retriever fetches the most relevant information, and the LLM generates a response based on that context to reduce hallucinations.

I also experimented with multi-source RAG by retrieving information from sources like Wikipedia, Arxiv, local PDFs, and repository documentation to improve response quality.

For orchestration, I used LangGraph because it supports stateful workflows with memory, conditional routing, tool calling, and human-in-the-loop approvals. I integrated a GitHub MCP server so the agent can safely interact with GitHub tools, such as searching issues or drafting pull requests, with user confirmation before performing sensitive actions.

I also implemented conversational memory using MemorySaver and used streaming and async streaming to provide real-time responses. During development, I used LangSmith to trace executions, debug workflows, and monitor the agent's behavior
